# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: corythucha-ciliata
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:corythucha-ciliata/animal-diversity-web] The **Animal Diversity Web** (**ADW**) is a non-profit group that hosts an online database site that collects natural history, classification, species characteristics, conservation biology, and distribution information on species of animals.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/animal-diversity-web] The website includes photographs, sound clips, and a virtual museum.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/animal-diversity-web] The local, relational database is written and maintained by staff and student contributors from the University of Michigan.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/animal-diversity-web] It can be accessed through the web and mobile apps.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/animal-diversity-web] It offers resources for schoolteachers ("K–12 instructors"), and functions as a virtual museum containing mostly mammals and a collection of skulls that can be virtually handled.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/animal-diversity-web] The ADW was created in 1995 by Philip Myers, a former biology professor at the University of Michigan.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/animal-diversity-web] As of June 2022, the site contained records for approximately 2,150 animal species, represented by 11,500 images and 725 sounds.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/animal-diversity-web] The ADW has over 250 accounts of higher taxonomic groups.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/animal-diversity-web] Most of the contributors to the website are undergraduate students.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/animal-diversity-web] ADW has collaborated with 30 colleges and universities across the United States.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/animal-diversity-web] The undergraduate students often submit reports on species as part of their course requirements.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/animal-diversity-web] Each account is edited by both the professors and the staff at the ADW.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/animal-diversity-web] As of November 2017, the Animal Diversity Web had 3,675 contributors.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/animal] The animal kingdom is divided into five major clades, namely Porifera, Ctenophora, Placozoa, Cnidaria and Bilateria.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/animal] The much smaller basal phylum Xenacoelomorpha have an uncertain position within Bilateria.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/animal] Animals first appeared in the fossil record in the late Cryogenian period and diversified in the subsequent Ediacaran period in what is known as the Avalon explosion.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/animal] Nearly all modern animal phyla first appeared in the fossil record as marine species during the Cambrian explosion, which began around 539 million years ago (Mya), and most classes during the Ordovician radiation 485.4 Mya.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/animal] Common to all living animals, 6,331 groups of genes have been identified that may have arisen from a single common ancestor that lived about 650 Mya during the Cryogenian period.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/animal] Historically, Aristotle divided animals into those with blood and those without.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/animal] Carl Linnaeus created the first hierarchical biological classification for animals in 1758 with his *Systema Naturae*, which Jean-Baptiste Lamarck expanded into 14 phyla by 1809.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/animal] In 1874, Ernst Haeckel divided the animal kingdom into the multicellular **Metazoa** (now synonymous with Animalia) and the Protozoa, single-celled organisms no longer considered animals.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/animal] In modern times, the biological classification of animals relies on advanced techniques, such as molecular phylogenetics, which are effective at demonstrating the evolutionary relationships between taxa.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/animal] Humans make use of many other animal species for food (including meat, eggs, and dairy products), for materials (such as leather, fur, and wool), as pets and as working animals for transportation, and services.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/animal] Dogs, the first domesticated animal, have been used in hunting, in security and in warfare, as have horses, pigeons and birds of prey; while other terrestrial and aquatic animals are hunted for sports, trophies or profits.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/animal] Non-human animals are also an important cultural element of human evolution, having appeared in cave arts and totems since the earliest times, and are frequently featured in mythology, religion, arts, literature, heraldry, politics, and sports.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/animal] The word *animal* comes from the Latin noun *animal* of the same meaning, which is itself derived from Latin *animalis* 'having breath or soul'.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/animal] The biological definition includes all members of the kingdom Animalia.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/animal] In colloquial usage, the term *animal* is often used to refer only to nonhuman animals.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/animal] The term *metazoa* is derived from Ancient Greek μετα *meta* 'after' (in biology, the prefix *meta-* stands for 'later') and ζῷᾰ *zōia* 'animals', plural of ζῷον *zōion* 'animal'.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/animal] A **metazoan** is any member of the group *Metazoa*.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/animal] Animals have several characteristics that they share with other living things.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/animal] Animals are eukaryotic, multicellular, and aerobic, as are plants and fungi.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/animal] Unlike plants and algae, which produce their own food, animals cannot produce their own food, a feature they share with fungi.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/animal] Animals ingest organic material and digest it internally.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/animal] Typically, there is an internal digestive chamber with either one opening (in Ctenophora, Cnidaria, and flatworms) or two openings (in most bilaterians).
[src:corythucha-ciliata/animal] Animal development is controlled by Hox genes, which signal the times and places to develop structures such as body segments and limbs.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/animal] During development, the animal extracellular matrix forms a relatively flexible framework upon which cells can move about and be reorganised into specialised tissues and organs, making the formation of complex structures possible, and allowing cells to be differentiated.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/animal] The extracellular matrix may be calcified, forming structures such as shells, bones, and spicules.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/animal] In contrast, the cells of other multicellular organisms (primarily algae, plants, and fungi) are held in place by cell walls, and so develop by progressive growth.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/animal] Nearly all animals make use of some form of sexual reproduction.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/animal] They produce haploid gametes by meiosis; the smaller, motile gametes are spermatozoa and the larger, non-motile gametes are ova.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/animal] These fuse to form zygotes, which develop via mitosis into a hollow sphere, called a blastula.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/animal] In sponges, blastula larvae swim to a new location, attach to the seabed, and develop into a new sponge.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/animal] In most other groups, the blastula undergoes more complicated rearrangement.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/animal] It first invaginates to form a gastrula with a digestive chamber and two separate germ layers, an external ectoderm and an internal endoderm.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/animal] In most cases, a third germ layer, the mesoderm, also develops between them.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/animal] These germ layers then differentiate to form tissues and organs.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/animal] Repeated instances of mating with a close relative during sexual reproduction generally leads to inbreeding depression within a population due to the increased prevalence of harmful recessive traits.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/animal] Animals have evolved numerous mechanisms for avoiding close inbreeding.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/animal] Some animals are capable of asexual reproduction, which often results in a genetic clone of the parent.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/animal] This may take place through fragmentation; budding, such as in *Hydra* and other cnidarians; or parthenogenesis, where fertile eggs are produced without mating, such as in aphids.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/animal] Animals are categorised into ecological groups depending on their trophic levels and how they consume organic material.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/animal] Such groupings include carnivores (further divided into subcategories such as piscivores, insectivores, ovivores, etc.), herbivores (subcategorised into folivores, graminivores, frugivores, granivores, nectarivores, algivores, etc.), omnivores, fungivores, scavengers/detritivores, and parasites.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/animal] Interactions between animals of each biome form complex food webs within that ecosystem.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/animal] In carnivorous or omnivorous species, predation is a consumer–resource interaction where the predator feeds on another organism, its prey, who often evolves anti-predator adaptations to avoid being fed upon.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/animal] Selective pressures imposed on one another lead to an evolutionary arms race between predator and prey, resulting in various antagonistic/competitive coevolutions.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/animal] Almost all multicellular predators are animals.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/animal] Some consumers use multiple methods; for example, in parasitoid wasps, the larvae feed on the hosts' living tissues, killing them in the process, but the adults primarily consume nectar from flowers.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/animal] Other animals may have very specific feeding behaviours, such as hawksbill sea turtles which mainly eat sponges.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/animal] Most animals rely on biomass and bioenergy produced by plants and phytoplanktons (collectively called producers) through photosynthesis.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/animal] Herbivores, as primary consumers, eat the plant material directly to digest and absorb the nutrients, while carnivores and other animals on higher trophic levels indirectly acquire the nutrients by eating the herbivores or other animals that have eaten the herbivores.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/animal] Animals oxidise carbohydrates, lipids, proteins and other biomolecules in cellular respiration, which allows the animal to grow and to sustain basal metabolism and fuel other biological processes such as locomotion.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/animal] Some benthic animals living close to hydrothermal vents and cold seeps on the dark sea floor consume organic matter produced through chemosynthesis (via oxidising inorganic compounds such as hydrogen sulfide) by archaea and bacteria.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/animal] Animals originated in the ocean; all extant animal phyla, except for Micrognathozoa and Onychophora, feature at least some marine species.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/animal] However, several lineages of arthropods begun to colonise land around the same time as land plants, between 510 and 471 million years ago, during the Late Cambrian or Early Ordovician periods.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/animal] Vertebrates such as the lobe-finned fish *Tiktaalik* started to move on to land in the late Devonian, about 375 million years ago.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/animal] Other notable animal groups that colonized land environments are Mollusca, Platyhelmintha, Annelida, Tardigrada, Onychophora, Rotifera, Nematoda.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/animal] Animals occupy virtually all of earth's habitats and microhabitats, with faunas adapted to salt water, hydrothermal vents, fresh water, hot springs, swamps, forests, pastures, deserts, air, and the interiors of other organisms.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/animal] Animals are however not particularly heat tolerant; very few of them can survive at constant temperatures above 50 °C (122 °F) or in the most extreme cold deserts of continental Antarctica.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/animal] The collective global geomorphic influence of animals on the processes shaping the Earth's surface remains largely understudied, with most studies limited to individual species and well-known exemplars.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/animal] The blue whale (*Balaenoptera musculus*) is the largest animal that has ever lived, weighing up to 190 tonnes and measuring up to 33.6 metres (110 ft) long.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/animal] The largest extant terrestrial animal is the African bush elephant (*Loxodonta africana*), weighing up to 12.25 tonnes and measuring up to 10.67 metres (35.0 ft) long.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/animal] The largest terrestrial animals that ever lived were titanosaur sauropod dinosaurs such as *Argentinosaurus*, which may have weighed as much as 73 tonnes, and *Supersaurus* which may have reached 39 metres.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/animal] Several animals are microscopic; some Myxozoa (obligate parasites within the Cnidaria) never grow larger than 20 μm, and one of the smallest species (*Myxobolus shekel*) is no more than 8.5 μm when fully grown.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/animal] The following table lists estimated numbers of described extant species for the major animal phyla, along with their principal habitats (terrestrial, fresh water, and marine), and free-living or parasitic ways of life.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/animal] Species estimates shown here are based on numbers described scientifically; much larger estimates have been calculated based on various means of prediction, and these can vary wildly.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/animal] For instance, around 25,000–27,000 species of nematodes have been described, while published estimates of the total number of nematode species include 10,000–20,000; 500,000; 10 million; and 100 million.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/animal] Using patterns within the taxonomic hierarchy, the total number of animal species—including those not yet described—was calculated to be about 7.77 million in 2011.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/animal] Evidence of animals is found as long ago as the Cryogenian period.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/animal] 24-Isopropylcholestane (24-ipc) has been found in rocks from roughly 650 million years ago; it is only produced by sponges and pelagophyte algae.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/animal] Its likely origin is from sponges based on molecular clock estimates for the origin of 24-ipc production in both groups.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/animal] Analyses of pelagophyte algae consistently recover a Phanerozoic origin, while analyses of sponges recover a Neoproterozoic origin, consistent with the appearance of 24-ipc in the fossil record.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/animal] The first body fossils of animals appear in the Ediacaran, represented by forms such as *Charnia* and *Spriggina*.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/animal] It had long been doubted whether these fossils truly represented animals, but the discovery of the animal lipid cholesterol in fossils of *Dickinsonia* establishes their nature.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/animal] Animals are thought to have originated under low-oxygen conditions, suggesting that they were capable of living entirely by anaerobic respiration, but as they became specialised for aerobic metabolism they became fully dependent on oxygen in their environments.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/animal] Many animal phyla first appear in the fossil record during the Cambrian explosion, starting about 539 million years ago, in beds such as the Burgess Shale.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/animal] Extant phyla in these rocks include molluscs, brachiopods, onychophorans, tardigrades, arthropods, echinoderms and hemichordates, along with numerous now-extinct forms such as the predatory *Anomalocaris*.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/animal] The apparent suddenness of the event may however be an artefact of the fossil record, rather than showing that all these animals appeared simultaneously.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/animal] That view is supported by the discovery of *Auroralumina attenboroughii*, the earliest known Ediacaran crown-group cnidarian (557–562 mya, some 20 million years before the Cambrian explosion) from Charnwood Forest, England.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/animal] It is thought to be one of the earliest predators, catching small prey with its nematocysts as modern cnidarians do.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/animal] Some palaeontologists have suggested that animals appeared much earlier than the Cambrian explosion, possibly as early as 1 billion years ago.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/animal] Early fossils that might represent animals appear for example in the 665-million-year-old rocks of the Trezona Formation of South Australia.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/animal] These fossils are interpreted as most probably being early sponges.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/animal] Trace fossils such as tracks and burrows found in the Tonian period (from 1 gya) may indicate the presence of triploblastic worm-like animals, roughly as large (about 5 mm wide) and complex as earthworms.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/animal] However, similar tracks are produced by the giant single-celled protist *Gromia sphaerica*, so the Tonian trace fossils may not indicate early animal evolution.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/animal] Around the same time, the layered mats of microorganisms called stromatolites decreased in diversity, perhaps due to grazing by newly evolved animals.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/animal] Objects such as sediment-filled tubes that resemble trace fossils of the burrows of wormlike animals have been found in 1.2 gya rocks in North America, in 1.5 gya rocks in Australia and North America, and in 1.7 gya rocks in Australia.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/animal] Their interpretation as having an animal origin is disputed, as they might be water-escape or other structures.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/animal] Animals are monophyletic, meaning they are derived from a common ancestor.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/animal] Animals are the sister group to the choanoflagellates, with which they form the Choanozoa.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/animal] Ros-Rocher and colleagues (2021) trace the origins of animals to unicellular ancestors, providing the external phylogeny shown in the cladogram.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/animal] Uncertainty of relationships is indicated with dashed lines.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/animal] The animal clade had certainly originated by 650 mya, and may have come into being as much as 800 mya, based on molecular clock evidence for different phyla.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/animal] The relationships at the base of the animal tree have been debated.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/animal] Other than Ctenophora, the Bilateria and Cnidaria are the only groups with symmetry, and other evidence shows they are closely related.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/animal] In addition to sponges, Placozoa has no symmetry and was often considered a "missing link" between protists and multicellular animals.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/animal] The presence of hox genes in Placozoa shows that they were once more complex.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/animal] The Porifera (sponges) have long been assumed to be sister to the rest of the animals, but there is evidence that the Ctenophora may be in that position.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/animal] Molecular phylogenetics has supported both the sponge-sister and ctenophore-sister hypotheses.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/animal] Sponges are physically very distinct from other animals, and were long thought to have diverged first, representing the oldest animal phylum and forming a sister clade to all other animals.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/animal] Despite their morphological dissimilarity with all other animals, genetic evidence suggests sponges may be more closely related to other animals than the comb jellies are.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/animal] Sponges lack the complex organisation found in most other animal phyla; their cells are differentiated, but in most cases not organised into distinct tissues, unlike all other animals.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/animal] Sponges are almost entirely sessile in their adult stage.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/animal] Sponges lack a digestive, circulatory, respiratory, or excretory system.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/animal] Instead, they rely on the flow of water through their bodies to perform these functions.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/animal] Many have adapted a hollow structure to facilitate the flow of water through their bodies.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/animal] They typically feed by drawing in water through pores, filtering out small particles of food.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/animal] They absorb oxygen dissolved in water, and they release carbon dioxide and nitrogenous waste into water that flows through them.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/animal] Sponges can reproduce sexually and asexually.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/animal] Asexual reproduction happens through a variety of mechanisms including by fragmentation, where a piece of the sponge splits off and reestablishes somewhere else.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/animal] For sexual reproduction, most sponges are hermaphrodites, they produce both egg and sperm cells.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/animal] Comb jellies, members of Ctenophora, are radially symmetric and have digestive chambers with a single opening, which serves as both mouth and anus.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/animal] Ctenophora have distinct tissues, but these are not organised into discrete organs.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/animal] They move using large arrays of cilia, called swimming plates.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/animal] They have are unique in having colloblasts, structures on their tentacles that help them catch prey.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/animal] They have nerve cells, but lack a brain or central nervous system.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/animal] Instead their nerves are arranged into a nerve net.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/animal] Their nerves are very different from those of other animals, and evidence suggests that their nerves developed independently of the nerves of other animals.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/animal] Like Ctenophora, Cnidaria are radially symmetric and have digestive chambers with a single opening, which serves as both mouth and anus.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/animal] They also have distinct tissues that are not organised into discrete organs.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/animal] Members of the group Anthozoa, such as sea anemones, coral, and sea pens only are sessile polyps.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/animal] Most members of Medusozoa, including jellyfish and most hydrozoans, have a polyp form as well, but also have a motile medusae stage.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/animal] The medusae stage are commonly known as jellyfish.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/animal] Cnidaria are diploblastic, having only two main germ layers, ectoderm and endoderm.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/animal] The tiny placozoans have no permanent digestive chamber and no symmetry; they superficially resemble amoebae.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/animal] Their phylogeny is poorly defined, and under active research.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/animal] The remaining animals, the great majority—comprising some 29 phyla and over a million species—form the Bilateria clade, which have a bilaterally symmetric body plan.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/animal] The Bilateria are triploblastic, with three well-developed germ layers, and their tissues form distinct organs.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/animal] The digestive chamber has two openings, a mouth and an anus, and in the Nephrozoa there is an internal body cavity, a coelom or pseudocoelom.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/animal] These animals have a head end (anterior) and a tail end (posterior), a back (dorsal) surface and a belly (ventral) surface, and a left and a right side.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/animal] A modern consensus phylogenetic tree for the Bilateria is shown below.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/animal] Having a front end means that this part of the body encounters stimuli, such as food, favouring cephalisation, the development of a head with sense organs and a mouth.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/animal] Many bilaterians have a combination of circular muscles that constrict the body, making it longer, and an opposing set of longitudinal muscles, that shorten the body; these enable soft-bodied animals with a hydrostatic skeleton to move by peristalsis.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/animal] They also have a gut that extends through the basically cylindrical body from mouth to anus.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/animal] Many bilaterian phyla have primary larvae which swim with cilia and have an apical organ containing sensory cells.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/animal] However, over evolutionary time, descendant spaces have evolved which have lost one or more of each of these characteristics.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/animal] For example, adult echinoderms are radially symmetric (unlike their larvae), while some parasitic worms have extremely simplified body structures.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/animal] Genetic studies have considerably changed zoologists' understanding of the relationships within the Bilateria.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/animal] Most appear to belong to two major lineages, the protostomes and the deuterostomes.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/animal] It is often suggested that the basalmost bilaterians are the Xenacoelomorpha, with all other bilaterians belonging to the subclade Nephrozoa.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/animal] However, this suggestion has been contested, with other studies finding that xenacoelomorphs are more closely related to Ambulacraria than to other bilaterians.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/animal] Protostomes and deuterostomes differ in several ways.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/animal] Early in development, deuterostome embryos undergo radial cleavage during cell division, while many protostomes (the Spiralia) undergo spiral cleavage.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/animal] Animals from both groups possess a complete digestive tract, but in protostomes the first opening of the embryonic gut develops into the mouth, and the anus forms secondarily.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/animal] In deuterostomes, the anus forms first while the mouth develops secondarily.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/animal] Most protostomes have schizocoelous development, where cells simply fill in the interior of the gastrula to form the mesoderm.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/animal] In deuterostomes, the mesoderm forms by enterocoelic pouching, through invagination of the endoderm.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/animal] The main deuterostome taxa are the Ambulacraria and the Chordata.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/animal] Ambulacraria are exclusively marine and include acorn worms, starfish, sea urchins, and sea cucumbers.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/animal] The chordates are dominated by the vertebrates (animals with backbones), which consist of fishes, amphibians, reptiles, birds, and mammals.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/animal] The protostomes include the Ecdysozoa, named after their shared trait of ecdysis, growth by moulting, Among the largest ecdysozoan phyla are the arthropods and the nematodes.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/animal] The rest of the protostomes are in the Spiralia, named for their pattern of developing by spiral cleavage in the early embryo.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/animal] Major spiralian phyla include the annelids and molluscs.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/animal] In the classical era, Aristotle divided animals, based on his own observations, into those with blood (roughly, the vertebrates) and those without.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/animal] In 1758, Carl Linnaeus created the first hierarchical classification in his *Systema Naturae*.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/animal] In his original scheme, the animals were one of three kingdoms, divided into the classes of Vermes, Insecta, Pisces, Amphibia, Aves, and Mammalia.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/animal] Since then, the last four have all been subsumed into a single phylum, the Chordata, while his Insecta (which included the crustaceans and arachnids) and Vermes have been renamed or broken up.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/animal] The process was begun in 1793 by Jean-Baptiste de Lamarck, who called the Vermes *une espèce de chaos* ('a chaotic mess') and split the group into three new phyla: worms, echinoderms, and polyps (which contained corals and jellyfish).
[src:corythucha-ciliata/animal] By 1809, in his *Philosophie Zoologique*, Lamarck had created nine phyla apart from vertebrates (where he still had four phyla: mammals, birds, reptiles, and fish) and molluscs, namely cirripedes, annelids, crustaceans, arachnids, insects, worms, radiates, polyps, and infusorians.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/animal] This division into four was followed by the embryologist Karl Ernst von Baer in 1828, the zoologist Louis Agassiz in 1857, and the comparative anatomist Richard Owen in 1860.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/animal] In 1874, Ernst Haeckel divided the animal kingdom into two subkingdoms: Metazoa (multicellular animals, with five phyla: coelenterates, echinoderms, articulates, molluscs, and vertebrates) and Protozoa (single-celled animals), including a sixth animal phylum, sponges.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/animal] The protozoa were later moved to the former kingdom Protista, leaving only the Metazoa as a synonym of Animalia.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/animal] The human population exploits a large number of other animal species for food, both of domesticated livestock species in animal husbandry and, mainly at sea, by hunting wild species.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/animal] Marine fish of many species are caught commercially for food.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/animal] A smaller number of species are farmed commercially.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/animal] Humans and their livestock make up more than 90% of the biomass of all terrestrial vertebrates, and almost as much as all insects combined.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/animal] Invertebrates including cephalopods, crustaceans, insects—principally bees and silkworms—and bivalve or gastropod molluscs are hunted or farmed for food, fibres.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/animal] Chickens, cattle, sheep, pigs, and other animals are raised as livestock for meat across the world.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/animal] Animal fibres such as wool and silk are used to make textiles, while animal sinews have been used as lashings and bindings, and leather is widely used to make shoes and other items.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/animal] Animals have been hunted and farmed for their fur to make items such as coats and hats.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/animal] Dyestuffs including carmine (cochineal), shellac, and kermes have been made from the bodies of insects.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/animal] Working animals including cattle and horses have been used for work and transport from the first days of agriculture.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/animal] Animals such as the fruit fly *Drosophila melanogaster* serve a major role in science as experimental models.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/animal] Animals have been used to create vaccines since their discovery in the 18th century.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/animal] Some medicines such as the cancer drug trabectedin are based on toxins or other molecules of animal origin.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/animal] People have used hunting dogs to help chase down and retrieve animals, and birds of prey to catch birds and mammals, while tethered cormorants have been used to catch fish.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/animal] Poison dart frogs have been used to poison the tips of blowpipe darts.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/animal] A wide variety of animals are kept as pets, from invertebrates such as tarantulas, octopuses, and praying mantises, reptiles such as snakes and chameleons, and birds including canaries, parakeets, and parrots all finding a place.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/animal] However, the most kept pet species are mammals, namely dogs, cats, and rabbits.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/animal] There is a tension between the role of animals as companions to humans, and their existence as individuals with rights of their own.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/animal] A wide variety of terrestrial and aquatic animals are hunted for sport.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/animal] The signs of the Western and Chinese zodiacs are based on animals.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/animal] In China and Japan, the butterfly has been seen as the personification of a person's soul, and in classical representation the butterfly is also the symbol of the soul.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/animal] Animals have been the subjects of art from the earliest times, both historical, as in ancient Egypt, and prehistoric, as in the cave paintings at Lascaux.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/animal] Major animal paintings include Albrecht Dürer's 1515 *The Rhinoceros*, and George Stubbs's c.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/animal] Insects, birds and mammals play roles in literature and film, such as in giant bug movies.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/animal] Animals including insects and mammals feature in mythology and religion.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/animal] The scarab beetle was sacred in ancient Egypt, and the cow is sacred in Hinduism.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/animal] Among other mammals, deer, horses, lions, bats, bears, and wolves are the subjects of myths and worship.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/arthropod-p01] Haemolymph is the analogue of blood for most arthropods.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/arthropod-p01] An arthropod has an open circulatory system, with a body cavity called a haemocoel through which haemolymph circulates to the interior organs.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/arthropod-p01] Like their exteriors, the internal organs of arthropods are generally built of repeated segments.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/arthropod-p01] They have ladder-like nervous systems, with paired ventral nerve cords running through all segments and forming paired ganglia in each segment.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/arthropod-p01] Their heads are formed by fusion of varying numbers of segments, and their brains are formed by fusion of the ganglia of these segments and encircle the esophagus.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/arthropod-p01] The respiratory and excretory systems of arthropods vary, depending as much on their environment as on the subphylum to which they belong.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/arthropod-p01] Arthropods use combinations of compound eyes and pigment-pit ocelli for vision.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/arthropod-p01] In most species, the ocelli can only detect the direction from which light is coming, and the compound eyes are the main source of information; however, in spiders, the main eyes are ocelli that can form images and, in a few cases, can swivel to track prey.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/arthropod-p01] Arthropods also have a wide range of chemical and mechanical sensors, mostly based on modifications of the many bristles known as setae that project through their cuticles.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/arthropod-p01] Similarly, their reproduction and development are varied; all terrestrial species use internal fertilization, but this is sometimes by indirect transfer of the sperm via an appendage or the ground, rather than by direct injection.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/arthropod-p01] Aquatic species use either internal or external fertilization.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/arthropod-p01] Almost all arthropods lay eggs, with many species giving birth to live young after the eggs have hatched inside the mother.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/arthropod-p01] Still, a few are genuinely viviparous, such as aphids.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/arthropod-p01] Arthropod hatchlings vary from miniature adults to grubs and caterpillars that lack jointed limbs and eventually undergo a total metamorphosis to produce the adult form.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/arthropod-p01] The level of maternal care for hatchlings varies from nonexistent to the prolonged care provided by social insects.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/arthropod-p01] The evolutionary ancestry of arthropods dates back to the Cambrian period.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/arthropod-p01] The group is generally regarded as monophyletic, and many analyses support the placement of arthropods with cycloneuralians (or their constituent clades) in a superphylum Ecdysozoa.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/arthropod-p01] Overall, however, the basal relationships of animals are not yet well resolved.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/arthropod-p01] Likewise, the relationships between various arthropod groups are still actively debated.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/arthropod-p01] Today, arthropods contribute to the human food supply both directly as food and more importantly, indirectly as pollinators of crops.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/arthropod-p01] Some species are known to spread severe disease to humans, livestock, and crops.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/arthropod-p01] The word *arthropod* comes from the Greek ἄρθρον *árthron* 'joint', and πούς *poús* (gen. ποδός *podós*) 'foot' or 'leg', which together mean "jointed leg", with the word "arthropodes" initially used in anatomical descriptions by Barthélemy Charles Joseph Dumortier published in 1832.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/arthropod-p01] The designation "Arthropoda" appears to have been first used in 1843 by the German zoologist Johann Ludwig Christian Gravenhorst (1777–1857).
[src:corythucha-ciliata/arthropod-p01] The origin of the name has been the subject of considerable confusion, with credit often given erroneously to Pierre André Latreille or Karl Theodor Ernst von Siebold instead, among various others.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/arthropod-p01] Terrestrial arthropods are often called bugs.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/arthropod-p01] Arthropods are invertebrates with segmented bodies and jointed limbs.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/arthropod-p01] The exoskeleton or cuticle consists of chitin, a polymer of *N*-acetylglucosamine.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/arthropod-p01] The cuticle of many crustaceans, beetle mites, the clades Penetini and Archaeoglenini inside the beetle subfamily Phrenapatinae, and millipedes (except for bristly millipedes) is also biomineralized with calcium carbonate.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/arthropod-p01] Calcification of the endosternite, an internal structure used for muscle attachments, also occurs in some opiliones, and the pupal cuticle of the fly *Bactrocera dorsalis* contains calcium phosphate.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/arthropod-p01] Arthropoda is the largest animal phylum, with the estimates of the number of arthropod species varying from 1,170,000 to 5~10 million and accounting for over 80 percent of all known living animal species.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/arthropod-p01] One arthropod sub-group, the insects, includes more described species than any other taxonomic class.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/arthropod-p01] The total number of species remains difficult to determine, as estimates rely on census counts at specific locations, scaled up and projected onto other regions, then totalled – allowing for double-counting – to cover the whole world.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/arthropod-p01] Modeling assumptions are involved at each stage, introducing uncertainty.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/arthropod-p01] A study in 1992 estimated that there were 500,000 species of animals and plants in Costa Rica alone, of which 365,000 were arthropods.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/arthropod-p01] They are important members of marine, freshwater, land and air ecosystems and one of only two major animal groups that have adapted to life in dry environments; the other is amniotes, whose living members are reptiles, birds and mammals.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/arthropod-p01] Both the smallest and largest arthropods are crustaceans.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/arthropod-p01] The smallest belong to the class Tantulocarida, some of which are less than 100 micrometres (0.0039 in) long.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/arthropod-p01] The largest are species in the class Malacostraca, with the legs of the Japanese spider crab potentially spanning up to 4 metres (13 ft) and the American lobster reaching weights over 20 kg (44 lbs).
[src:corythucha-ciliata/arthropod-p01] The embryos of all arthropods are segmented, consisting of a series of repeated modules.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/arthropod-p01] The last common ancestor of living arthropods probably consisted of a series of undifferentiated segments, each with a pair of appendages that functioned as limbs.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/arthropod-p01] However, all known living and fossil arthropods have grouped segments into tagmata in which segments and their limbs are specialized in various ways.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/arthropod-p01] The three-part appearance of many insect bodies and the two-part appearance of spiders is a result of this grouping.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/arthropod-p01] There are no external signs of segmentation in mites.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/arthropod-p01] Arthropods also have two body elements that are not part of this serially repeated pattern of segments, an ocular somite at the front, where the mouth and eyes originated, and a telson at the rear, behind the anus.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/arthropod-p01] Originally, it seems that each appendage-bearing segment had two separate pairs of appendages: an upper, unsegmented exite and a lower, segmented endopod.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/arthropod-p01] These would later fuse into a single pair of biramous appendages united by a basal segment (protopod or basipod), with the upper branch acting as a gill while the lower branch was used for locomotion.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/arthropod-p01] The appendages of most crustaceans and some extinct taxa such as trilobites have another segmented branch known as exopods, but whether these structures have a single origin remain controversial.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/arthropod-p01] Alignment of anterior body segments and appendages across various arthropod taxa, based on the observations until the mid 2010s.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/arthropod-p01] The most conspicuous specialization of segments is in the head.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/arthropod-p01] Despite myriapods and hexapods both having similar head combinations, hexapods are deeply nested within crustacea while myriapods are not, so these traits are believed to have evolved separately.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/arthropod-p01] In addition, some extinct arthropods, such as *Marrella*, belong to none of these groups, as their heads are formed by their own particular combinations of segments and specialized appendages.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/arthropod-p01] Working out the evolutionary stages by which all these different combinations could have appeared is so difficult that it has long been known as "The arthropod head problem".
[src:corythucha-ciliata/arthropod-p01] Snodgrass even hoped it would not be solved, as he found trying to work out solutions to be fun.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/arthropod-p01] Arthropod exoskeletons are made of cuticle, a non-cellular material secreted by the epidermis.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/arthropod-p01] The exocuticle and endocuticle together are known as the procuticle.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/arthropod-p01] Each body segment and limb section is encased in hardened cuticle.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/arthropod-p01] The joints between body segments and between limb sections are covered by flexible cuticle.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/arthropod-p01] The exoskeletons of most aquatic crustaceans are biomineralized with calcium carbonate extracted from the water.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/arthropod-p01] Some terrestrial crustaceans have developed means of storing the mineral, since on land they cannot rely on a steady supply of dissolved calcium carbonate.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/arthropod-p01] Biomineralization generally affects the exocuticle and the outer part of the endocuticle.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/arthropod-p01] The cuticle may have setae (bristles) growing from special cells in the epidermis.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/arthropod-p01] Setae are as varied in form and function as appendages.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/arthropod-p01] The exoskeleton cannot stretch and thus restricts growth.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/arthropod-p01] Arthropods, therefore, replace their exoskeletons by undergoing ecdysis (moulting), or shedding the old exoskeleton, the exuviae, after growing a new one that is not yet hardened.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/arthropod-p01] Moulting cycles run nearly continuously until an arthropod reaches full size.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/arthropod-p01] The developmental stages between each moult (ecdysis) until sexual maturity is reached is called an instar.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/arthropod-p01] Differences between instars can often be seen in altered body proportions, colors, patterns, changes in the number of body segments or head width.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/arthropod-p01] After moulting, i.e. shedding their exoskeleton, the juvenile arthropods continue in their life cycle until they either pupate or moult again.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/arthropod-p01] In the initial phase of moulting, the animal stops feeding and its epidermis releases moulting fluid, a mixture of enzymes that digests the endocuticle and thus detaches the old cuticle.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/arthropod-p01] This phase begins when the epidermis has secreted a new epicuticle to protect it from the enzymes, and the epidermis secretes the new exocuticle while the old cuticle is detaching.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/arthropod-p01] When this stage is complete, the animal's body swells by taking in a large quantity of water or air, causing the old cuticle to split along predefined weaknesses where the old exocuticle was thinnest.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/arthropod-p01] It commonly takes several minutes for the animal to struggle out of the old cuticle.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/arthropod-p01] At this point, the new one is wrinkled and so soft that the animal cannot support itself and finds it very difficult to move, and the new endocuticle has not yet formed.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/arthropod-p01] The animal continues to pump itself up to stretch the new cuticle as much as possible, then hardens the new exocuticle and eliminates the excess air or water.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/arthropod-p01] By the end of this phase, the new endocuticle has formed.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/arthropod-p01] Many arthropods then eat the discarded cuticle to reclaim its materials.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/arthropod-p01] Because arthropods are unprotected and nearly immobilized until the new cuticle has hardened, they are in danger both of being trapped in the old cuticle and of being attacked by predators.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/arthropod-p01] Moulting may be responsible for 80 to 90% of all arthropod deaths.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/arthropod-p01] Arthropod bodies are also segmented internally, and the nervous, muscular, circulatory, and excretory systems have repeated components.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/arthropod-p01] Arthropods come from a lineage of animals that have a coelom, a membrane-lined cavity between the gut and the body wall that accommodates the internal organs.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/arthropod-p01] The strong, segmented limbs of arthropods eliminate the need for one of the coelom's main ancestral functions, as a hydrostatic skeleton, which muscles compress in order to change the animal's shape and thus enable it to move.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/arthropod-p01] Hence the coelom of the arthropod is reduced to small areas around the reproductive and excretory systems.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/arthropod-p01] Its place is largely taken by a hemocoel, a cavity that runs most of the length of the body and through which blood flows.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/arthropod-p01] Arthropods have open circulatory systems.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/arthropod-p01] Most have a few short, open-ended arteries.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/arthropod-p01] In chelicerates and crustaceans, the blood carries oxygen to the tissues, while hexapods use a separate system of tracheae.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/arthropod-p01] Many crustaceans and a few chelicerates and tracheates use respiratory pigments to assist oxygen transport.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/arthropod-p01] The most common respiratory pigment in arthropods is copper-based hemocyanin; this is used by many crustaceans and a few centipedes.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/arthropod-p01] A few crustaceans and insects use iron-based haemoglobin, the respiratory pigment used by vertebrates.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/arthropod-p01] As with other invertebrates, the respiratory pigments of those arthropods that have them are generally dissolved in the blood and rarely enclosed in corpuscles as they are in vertebrates.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/arthropod-p01] The heart is a muscular tube that runs just under the back and for most of the length of the hemocoel.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/arthropod-p01] It contracts in ripples that run from rear to front, pushing blood forwards.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/arthropod-p01] Sections not being squeezed by the heart muscle are expanded either by elastic ligaments or by small muscles, in either case connecting the heart to the body wall.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/arthropod-p01] Along the heart run a series of paired ostia, non-return valves that allow blood to enter the heart but prevent it from leaving before it reaches the front.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/arthropod-p01] Arthropods have a wide variety of respiratory systems.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/arthropod-p01] Small species often do not have any, since their high ratio of surface area to volume enables simple diffusion through the body surface to supply enough oxygen.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/arthropod-p01] Crustacea usually have gills that are modified appendages.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/arthropod-p01] Tracheae, systems of branching tunnels that run from the openings in the body walls, deliver oxygen directly to individual cells in many insects, myriapods and arachnids.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/arthropod-p01] Living arthropods have paired main nerve cords running along their bodies below the gut, and in each segment the cords form a pair of ganglia from which sensory and motor nerves run to other parts of the segment.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/arthropod-p01] Although the pairs of ganglia in each segment often appear physically fused, they are connected by commissures (relatively large bundles of nerves), which give arthropod nervous systems a characteristic ladder-like appearance.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/arthropod-p01] The brain is in the head, encircling and mainly above the oesophagus.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/arthropod-p01] It consists of the fused ganglia of the acron and one or two of the foremost segments that form the head – a total of three pairs of ganglia in most arthropods, but only two in chelicerates, which do not have antennae or the ganglion connected to them.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/arthropod-p01] The ganglia of other head segments are often close to the brain and function as part of it.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/arthropod-p01] In insects, these other head ganglia combine into a pair of subesophageal ganglia, under and behind the oesophagus.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/arthropod-p01] Spiders take this process a step further, as all the segmental ganglia are incorporated into the subesophageal ganglia, which occupy most of the space in the cephalothorax (front "super-segment").
[src:corythucha-ciliata/arthropod-p01] There are two different types of arthropod excretory systems.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/arthropod-p01] In aquatic arthropods, the end-product of biochemical reactions that metabolise nitrogen is ammonia, which is so toxic that it needs to be diluted as much as possible with water.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/arthropod-p01] The ammonia is then eliminated via any permeable membrane, mainly through the gills.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/arthropod-p01] All crustaceans use this system, and its high consumption of water may be responsible for the relative lack of success of crustaceans as land animals.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/arthropod-p01] Most aquatic arthropods and some terrestrial ones also have organs called nephridia ("little kidneys"), which extract other wastes for excretion as urine.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/arthropod-p01] The stiff cuticles of arthropods would block out information about the outside world, except that they are penetrated by many sensors or connections from sensors to the nervous system.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/arthropod-p01] In fact, arthropods have modified their cuticles into elaborate arrays of sensors.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/arthropod-p01] Various touch sensors, mostly setae, respond to different levels of force, from strong contact to very weak air currents.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/arthropod-p01] Chemical sensors provide equivalents of taste and smell, often by means of setae.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/arthropod-p01] Pressure sensors often take the form of membranes that function as eardrums, but are connected directly to nerves rather than to auditory ossicles.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/arthropod-p01] The antennae of most hexapods include sensor packages that monitor humidity, moisture and temperature.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/arthropod-p01] Most arthropods lack balance and acceleration sensors, and rely on their eyes to tell them which way is up.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/arthropod-p01] The self-righting behaviour of cockroaches is triggered when pressure sensors on the underside of the feet report no pressure.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/arthropod-p01] However, many malacostracan crustaceans have statocysts, which provide the same sort of information as the balance and motion sensors of the vertebrate inner ear.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/arthropod-p01] The proprioceptors of arthropods, sensors that report the force exerted by muscles and the degree of bending in the body and joints, are well understood.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/arthropod-p01] However, little is known about what other internal sensors arthropods may have.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/arthropod-p01] Arthropods may have sophisticated visual systems that include one or more usually both of compound eyes and pigment-cup ocelli, ("little eyes").
[src:corythucha-ciliata/arthropod-p01] In most cases, ocelli are only capable of detecting the direction from which light is coming, using the shadow cast by the walls of the cup, although the main eyes of spiders are pigment-cup ocelli that are capable of forming images, and those of jumping spiders can rotate to track prey.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/arthropod-p01] Compound eyes consist of fifteen to several thousand independent ommatidia, columns that are usually hexagonal in cross section.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/arthropod-p01] Each ommatidium is an independent sensor, with its own light-sensitive cells and often with its own lens and cornea.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/arthropod-p01] Compound eyes have a wide field of view, and can detect fast movement and, in some cases, the polarization of light.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/arthropod-p01] On the other hand, the relatively large size of ommatidia makes the images rather coarse, and compound eyes are shorter-sighted than those of birds and mammals – although this is not a severe disadvantage, as objects and events within 20 cm (8 in) are most important to most arthropods.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/arthropod-p01] Several arthropods have colour vision, and that of some insects has been studied in detail; for example, the ommatidia of bees contain receptors for both green and ultra-violet.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/arthropod-p01] A few arthropods, such as barnacles, are hermaphroditic, that is, each can have the organs of both sexes.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/arthropod-p01] However, individuals of most species remain of one sex their entire lives.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/arthropod-p01] A few species of insects and crustaceans can reproduce by parthenogenesis, especially if conditions favour a "population explosion".
[src:corythucha-ciliata/arthropod-p01] However, most arthropods rely on sexual reproduction, and parthenogenetic species often revert to sexual reproduction when conditions become less favourable.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/arthropod-p01] The ability to undergo meiosis is widespread among arthropods including both those that reproduce sexually and those that reproduce parthenogenetically.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/arthropod-p01] Although meiosis is a major characteristic of arthropods, understanding of its fundamental adaptive benefit has long been regarded as an unresolved problem, that appears to have remained unsettled.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/arthropod-p01] Aquatic arthropods may breed by external fertilization, as for example horseshoe crabs do, or by internal fertilization, where the ova remain in the female's body and the sperm must somehow be inserted.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/arthropod-p01] All known terrestrial arthropods use internal fertilization.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/arthropod-p01] Opiliones (harvestmen), millipedes, and some crustaceans use modified appendages such as gonopods or penises to transfer the sperm directly to the female.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/arthropod-p01] However, most male terrestrial arthropods produce spermatophores, waterproof packets of sperm, which the females take into their bodies.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/arthropod-p01] A few such species rely on females to find spermatophores that have already been deposited on the ground, but in most cases males only deposit spermatophores when complex courtship rituals look likely to be successful.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/arthropod-p01] Most arthropods lay eggs, but scorpions are ovoviviparous: they produce live young after the eggs have hatched inside the mother, and are noted for prolonged maternal care.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/arthropod-p01] Newly born arthropods have diverse forms, and insects alone cover the range of extremes.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/arthropod-p01] Some hatch as apparently miniature adults (direct development), and in some cases, such as silverfish, the hatchlings do not feed and may be helpless until after their first moult.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/arthropod-p01] Many insects (Holometabola) hatch as grubs or caterpillars, which do not have segmented limbs or hardened cuticles, and metamorphose into adult forms by entering an inactive phase in which the larval tissues are broken down and re-used to build the adult body.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/arthropod-p01] Dragonfly larvae have the typical cuticles and jointed limbs of arthropods but are flightless water-breathers with extendable jaws.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/arthropod-p01] Crustaceans commonly hatch as tiny nauplius larvae that have only three segments and pairs of appendages.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/arthropod-p01] Based on the distribution of shared plesiomorphic features in extant and fossil taxa, the last common ancestor of all arthropods is inferred to have been as a modular organism with each module covered by its own sclerite (armour plate) and bearing a pair of biramous limbs.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/arthropod-p01] However, whether the ancestral limb was uniramous or biramous is far from a settled debate.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/arthropod-p01] This Ur-arthropod had a ventral mouth, pre-oral antennae and dorsal eyes at the front of the body.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/arthropod-p01] It has been proposed that the Ediacaran animals *Parvancorina* and *Spriggina*, from around 555 million years ago, were arthropods, but later study shows that their affinities of being origin of arthropods are not reliable.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/arthropod-p01] Small arthropods with bivalve-like shells have been found in Early Cambrian fossil beds dating 541 to 539 million years ago in China and Australia.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/arthropod-p01] The earliest Cambrian trilobite fossils are about 520 million years old, but the class was already quite diverse and worldwide, suggesting that they had been around for quite some time.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/arthropod-p01] In the Maotianshan shales, which date back to 518 million years ago, arthropods such as *Kylinxia* and *Erratus* have been found that seem to represent transitional fossils between stem (e.g.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/arthropod-p01] Radiodonta such as *Anomalocaris*) and true arthropods.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/arthropod-p01] Re-examination in the 1970s of the Burgess Shale fossils from about 505 million years ago identified many arthropods, some of which could not be assigned to any of the well-known groups, and thus intensified the debate about the Cambrian explosion.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/arthropod-p01] A fossil of *Marrella* from the Burgess Shale has provided the earliest clear evidence of moulting.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/arthropod-p01] The earliest fossil of likely pancrustacean larvae date from about 514 million years ago in the Cambrian, followed by unique taxa like *Yicaris* and *Wujicaris*.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/arthropod-p01] The purported pancrustacean/crustacean affinity of some cambrian arthropods (e.g.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/arthropod-p01] Phosphatocopina, Bradoriida and Hymenocarine taxa like waptiids) were disputed by subsequent studies, as they might branch before the mandibulate crown-group.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/arthropod-p01] Within the pancrustacean crown-group, only Malacostraca, Branchiopoda and Pentastomida have Cambrian fossil records.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/arthropod-p01] Crustacean fossils are common from the Ordovician period onwards.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/arthropod-p01] They have remained almost entirely aquatic, possibly because they never developed excretory systems that conserve water.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/arthropod-p01] Arthropods provide the earliest identifiable fossils of land animals, from about 419 million years ago in the Late Silurian, and terrestrial tracks from about 450 million years ago appear to have been made by arthropods.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/arthropod-p01] Arthropods possessed attributes that were easily coopted for life on land; their existing jointed exoskeletons provided protection against desiccation, support against gravity and a means of locomotion that was not dependent on water.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/arthropod-p01] Around the same time the aquatic, scorpion-like eurypterids became the largest ever arthropods, some as long as 2.5 m (8 ft 2 in).
[src:corythucha-ciliata/arthropod-p01] The oldest known arachnid is the trigonotarbid *Palaeotarbus jerami*, from about 420 million years ago in the Silurian period.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/arthropod-p01] *Attercopus fimbriunguis*, from 386 million years ago in the Devonian period, bears the earliest known silk-producing spigots, but its lack of spinnerets means it was not one of the true spiders, which first appear in the Late Carboniferous over 299 million years ago.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/arthropod-p01] The Jurassic and Cretaceous periods provide a large number of fossil spiders, including representatives of many modern families.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/arthropod-p01] The oldest known scorpion is *Dolichophonus,* dated back to 436 million years ago.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/arthropod-p01] Lots of Silurian and Devonian scorpions were previously thought to be gill-breathing, hence the idea that scorpions were primitively aquatic and evolved air-breathing book lungs later on.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/arthropod-p01] However subsequent studies reveal most of them lacking reliable evidence for an aquatic lifestyle, while exceptional aquatic taxa (e.g.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/arthropod-p01] *Waeringoscorpio*) most likely derived from terrestrial scorpion ancestors.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/arthropod-p01] The oldest fossil record of hexapod is obscure, as most of the candidates are poorly preserved and their hexapod affinities had been disputed.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/arthropod-p01] An iconic example is the Devonian *Rhyniognatha hirsti*, dated at 396 to 407 million years ago, its mandibles are thought to be a type found only in winged insects, which suggests that the earliest insects appeared in the Silurian period.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/arthropod-p01] However, later study shows that *Rhyniognatha* most likely represent a myriapod, not even a hexapod.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/arthropod-p01] The unequivocal oldest known hexapod is the springtail *Rhyniella*, from about 410 million years ago in the Devonian period, and the palaeodictyopteran *Delitzschala bitterfeldensis*, from about 325 million years ago in the Carboniferous period, respectively.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/arthropod-p01] The Mazon Creek lagerstätten from the Late Carboniferous, about 300 million years ago, include about 200 species, some gigantic by modern standards, and indicate that insects had occupied their main modern ecological niches as herbivores, detritivores and insectivores.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/arthropod-p01] Social termites and ants first appear in the Early Cretaceous, and advanced social bees have been found in Late Cretaceous rocks but did not become abundant until the Middle Cenozoic.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/arthropod-p01] From 1952 to 1977, zoologist Sidnie Manton and others argued that arthropods are polyphyletic, in other words, that they do not share a common ancestor that was itself an arthropod.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/arthropod-p01] Instead, they proposed that three separate groups of "arthropods" evolved separately from common worm-like ancestors: the chelicerates, including spiders and scorpions; the crustaceans; and the uniramia, consisting of onychophorans, myriapods and hexapods.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/arthropod-p01] These arguments usually bypassed trilobites, as the evolutionary relationships of this class were unclear.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/arthropod-p01] Further analysis and discoveries in the 1990s reversed this view, and led to acceptance that arthropods are monophyletic, in other words they are inferred to share a common ancestor that was itself an arthropod.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/arthropod-p01] These changes made the scope of the term "arthropod" unclear, and Claus Nielsen proposed that the wider group should be labelled "Panarthropoda" ("all the arthropods") while the animals with jointed limbs and hardened cuticles should be called "Euarthropoda" ("true arthropods").
[src:corythucha-ciliata/arthropod-p01] A contrary view was presented in 2003, when Jan Bergström and Hou Xian-guang argued that, if arthropods were a "sister-group" to any of the anomalocarids, they must have lost and then re-evolved features that were well-developed in the anomalocarids.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/arthropod-p01] The earliest known arthropods ate mud in order to extract food particles from it, and possessed variable numbers of segments with unspecialized appendages that functioned as both gills and legs.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/arthropod-p01] Anomalocarids were, by the standards of the time, huge and sophisticated predators with specialized mouths and grasping appendages, fixed numbers of segments some of which were specialized, tail fins, and gills that were very different from those of arthropods.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/arthropod-p01] In 2006, they suggested that arthropods were more closely related to lobopods and tardigrades than to anomalocarids.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/arthropod-p01] In 2014, it was found that tardigrades were more closely related to arthropods than velvet worms.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/arthropod-p01] Higher up the "family tree", the Annelida have traditionally been considered the closest relatives of the Panarthropoda, since both groups have segmented bodies, and the combination of these groups was labelled Articulata.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/arthropod-p01] There had been competing proposals that arthropods were closely related to other groups such as nematodes, priapulids and tardigrades, but these remained minority views because it was difficult to specify in detail the relationships between these groups.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/arthropod-p01] In the 1990s, molecular phylogenetic analyses of DNA sequences produced a coherent scheme showing arthropods as members of a superphylum labelled Ecdysozoa ("animals that moult"), which contained nematodes, priapulids and tardigrades but excluded annelids.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/arthropod-p01] This hypothesis groups annelids with molluscs and brachiopods in another superphylum, Lophotrochozoa.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/arthropod-p01] If the Ecdysozoa hypothesis is correct, then segmentation of arthropods and annelids either has evolved convergently or has been inherited from a much older ancestor and subsequently lost in several other lineages, such as the non-arthropod members of the Ecdysozoa.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/arthropod-p01] *Marrella* was the first one to be recognized as significantly different from the well-known groups.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/arthropod-p01] The Deuteropoda is a recently established clade uniting the crown-group (living) arthropods with these possible "upper stem-group" fossils taxa.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/arthropod-p01] The clade is defined by important changes to the structure of the head region such as the appearance of a differentiated deutocerebral appendage pair, which excludes more basal taxa like radiodonts and "gilled lobopodians".
[src:corythucha-ciliata/arthropod-p01] Controversies remain about the positions of various extinct arthropod groups.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/arthropod-p01] Some studies recover Megacheira as closely related to chelicerates, while others recover them as outside the group containing Chelicerate and Mandibulata as stem-group euarthropods.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/arthropod-p01] The placement of the Artiopoda (which contains the extinct trilobites and similar forms) is also a frequent subject of dispute.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/arthropod-p01] The main hypotheses position them in the clade Arachnomorpha with the Chelicerates.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/arthropod-p01] However, one of the newer hypotheses is that the chelicerae have originated from the same pair of appendages that evolved into antennae in the ancestors of Mandibulata, which would place trilobites, which had antennae, closer to Mandibulata than Chelicerata, in the clade Antennulata.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/arthropod-p01] The fuxianhuiids, usually suggested to be stem-group arthropods, have been suggested to be Mandibulates in some recent studies.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/arthropod-p01] The Hymenocarina, a group of bivalved arthropods, previously thought to have been stem-group members of the group, have been demonstrated to be mandibulates based on the presence of mandibles.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/arthropod-p01] **Chelicerates** comprise the marine sea spiders and horseshoe crabs, along with the terrestrial arachnids such as mites, harvestmen, spiders, scorpions and related organisms characterized by the presence of chelicerae, appendages just above/in front of the mouthparts.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/arthropod-p01] Chelicerae appear in scorpions and horseshoe crabs as tiny claws that they use in feeding, but those of spiders have developed as fangs that inject venom.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/arthropod-p01] **Myriapods** comprise millipedes, centipedes, pauropods and symphylans, characterized by having numerous body segments each of which bearing one or two pairs of legs (or in a few cases being legless).
[src:corythucha-ciliata/arthropod-p01] All members are exclusively terrestrial.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/arthropod-p01] **Pancrustaceans** comprise ostracods, barnacles, copepods, malacostracans, cephalocaridans, branchiopods, remipedes and hexapods.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/arthropod-p01] Most groups are primarily aquatic (two notable exceptions being woodlice and hexapods, which are both purely terrestrial) and are characterized by having biramous appendages.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/arthropod-p01] The most abundant group of pancrustaceans are the terrestrial hexapods, which comprise insects, diplurans, springtails, and proturans, with six thoracic legs.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/arthropod-p01] The phylogeny of the major extant arthropod groups has been an area of considerable interest and dispute.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/arthropod-p01] Recent studies strongly suggest that Crustacea, as traditionally defined, is paraphyletic, with Hexapoda having evolved from within it, so that Crustacea and Hexapoda form a clade, Pancrustacea.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/arthropod-p01] The position of Myriapoda, Chelicerata and Pancrustacea remains unclear as of April 2012.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/arthropod-p01] In some studies, Myriapoda is grouped with Chelicerata (forming Myriochelata); in other studies, Myriapoda is grouped with Pancrustacea (forming Mandibulata), or Myriapoda may be sister to Chelicerata plus Pancrustacea.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/arthropod-p02] Crustaceans such as crabs, lobsters, crayfish, shrimp, and prawns have long been part of human cuisine, and are now raised commercially.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/arthropod-p02] Insects and their grubs are at least as nutritious as meat, and are eaten both raw and cooked in many cultures, though not most European, Hindu, and Islamic cultures.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/arthropod-p02] Cooked tarantulas are considered a delicacy in Cambodia, and by the Piaroa Indians of southern Venezuela, after the highly irritant hairs – the spider's main defence system – are removed.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/arthropod-p02] Humans also unintentionally eat arthropods in other foods, and food safety regulations lay down acceptable contamination levels for different kinds of food material.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/arthropod-p02] The intentional cultivation of arthropods and other small animals for human food, referred to as minilivestock, is now emerging in animal husbandry as an ecologically sound concept.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/arthropod-p02] Commercial butterfly breeding provides Lepidoptera stock to butterfly conservatories, educational exhibits, schools, research facilities, and cultural events.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/arthropod-p02] Besides pollinating, bees produce honey, which is the basis of a rapidly growing industry and international trade.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/arthropod-p02] The red dye cochineal, produced from a Central American species of insect, was economically important to the Aztecs and Mayans.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/arthropod-p02] While the region was under Spanish control, it became Mexico's second most-lucrative export, and is now regaining some of the ground it lost to synthetic competitors.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/arthropod-p02] Shellac, a resin secreted by a species of insect native to southern Asia, was historically used in great quantities for many applications in which it has mostly been replaced by synthetic resins, but it is still used in woodworking and as a food additive.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/arthropod-p02] The blood of horseshoe crabs contains a clotting agent, limulus amebocyte lysate, which is now used to test that antibiotics and kidney machines are free of dangerous bacteria, and to detect spinal meningitis.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/arthropod-p02] Forensic entomology uses evidence provided by arthropods to establish the time and sometimes the place of death of a human, and in some cases the cause.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/arthropod-p02] Recently insects have also gained attention as potential sources of drugs and other medicinal substances.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/arthropod-p02] The relative simplicity of the arthropods' body plan, allowing them to move on a variety of surfaces both on land and in water, have made them useful as models for robotics.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/arthropod-p02] The redundancy provided by segments allows arthropods and biomimetic robots to move normally, even with damaged or lost appendages.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/arthropod-p02] Although arthropods are the most numerous phylum on Earth, and thousands of arthropod species are venomous, they inflict relatively few serious bites and stings on humans.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/arthropod-p02] Far more serious are the effects on humans of diseases like malaria carried by blood-sucking insects.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/arthropod-p02] Other blood-sucking insects infect livestock with diseases that kill many animals and greatly reduce the usefulness of others.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/arthropod-p02] Ticks can cause tick paralysis and several parasite-borne diseases in humans.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/arthropod-p02] A few of the closely related mites also infest humans, causing intense itching, and others cause allergic diseases, including hay fever, asthma, and eczema.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/arthropod-p02] Many species of arthropods, principally insects but also mites, are agricultural and forest pests.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/arthropod-p02] The mite *Varroa destructor* has become the largest single problem faced by beekeepers worldwide.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/arthropod-p02] Efforts to control arthropod pests by large-scale use of pesticides have caused long-term effects on human health and on biodiversity.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/arthropod-p02] Increasing arthropod resistance to pesticides has led to the development of integrated pest management using a wide range of measures including biological control.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/arthropod-p02] Predatory mites may be useful in controlling some mite pests.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/australian-faunal-directory] The **Australian Faunal Directory** is an online catalogue of taxonomic and biological information on all animal species known to occur within Australia.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/australian-faunal-directory] It is a database produced by the Department of Climate Change, Energy, the Environment and Water of the Government of Australia.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/australian-faunal-directory] By 12 May 2021, the directory had collected information on about 126,442 species and subspecies.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/australian-faunal-directory] It includes the data from the discontinued *Zoological Catalogue of Australia* and is regularly updated.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/australian-faunal-directory] Started in the 1980s, its goal is compile a "list of all Australian fauna including terrestrial vertebrates, ants and marine fauna" and create an "Australian biotaxonomic information system".
[src:corythucha-ciliata/barcode-of-life-data-system] The **Barcode of Life Data System** (commonly known as **BOLD** or **BOLDSystems**) is a web platform specifically devoted to DNA barcoding.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/barcode-of-life-data-system] It is a cloud-based data storage and analysis platform developed at the Centre for Biodiversity Genomics in Canada.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/barcode-of-life-data-system] It consists of four main modules, a data portal, an educational portal, a registry of BINs (putative species), and a data collection and analysis workbench which provides an online platform for analyzing DNA sequences.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/barcode-of-life-data-system] Since its launch in 2005, BOLD has been extended to provide a range of functionality including data organization, validation, visualization and publication.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/barcode-of-life-data-system] The most recent version of the system, version 5, launched in 2024.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/barcode-of-life-data-system] Version 4, launched in 2017, brought a set of improvements supporting data collection and analysis but also included novel functionality improving data dissemination, citation, and annotation.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/barcode-of-life-data-system] Before November 16, 2020, BOLD already contained barcode sequences for 318,105 formally described species covering animals, plants, fungi, protists (with ~8.9 million specimens).
[src:corythucha-ciliata/barcode-of-life-data-system] Data release of BOLD mainly originated from a project BARCODE 500K executed by the International Barcode of Life (iBOL) Consortium from 2010 to 2015.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/barcode-of-life-data-system] It aimed for data acquisition of DNA barcode records for 5M specimens representing 500K species.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/barcode-of-life-data-system] All the specimens collection, sequences assignment, information sorting are contributed by great amount of scientists, collaborators and facilities from nations over the world.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/barcode-of-life-data-system] Data accumulation increases the accuracy of DNA barcode identification and facilitates the attainment of barcoding of life.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/bedfordshire] The county has an area of 1,235 km2 (477 sq mi) and had an estimated population of 749,943 in 2024.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/bedfordshire] Luton is in the south of the county, and Dunstable neighbours it to the west.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/bedfordshire] Leighton Buzzard is in the south-west, and Bedford in the centre-north.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/bedfordshire] For local government purposes Bedfordshire comprises three unitary authority areas: Bedford, Central Bedfordshire, and Luton.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/bedfordshire] The centre of Bedfordshire is a gently undulating clay plateau, out of which rises a ridge of greensand that runs south-west to north-east and which has a distinct north-facing escarpment.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/bedfordshire] The south of the county, around Luton, contains part of the chalk Chiltern Hills, and the north of the county part of a limestone ridge that runs between Milton Keynes and Northampton.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/bedfordshire] The county's highest point is at 243 m (797 ft) on the Dunstable Downs, which are part of the Chilterns.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/bedfordshire] The River Great Ouse flows through Bedfordshire, entering upstream of Harrold in the north-east and flowing in a circuitous but broadly southerly route to Bedford before turning north-east to exit the county upstream of St Neots in Cambridgeshire.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/bedfordshire] The first recorded use of the name in 1011 was "Bedanfordscir", meaning the shire or county of Bedford, which itself means "Beda's ford" (river crossing).
[src:corythucha-ciliata/bedfordshire] Bedfordshire was historically divided into nine hundreds: Barford, Biggleswade, Clifton, Flitt, Manshead, Redbornestoke, Stodden, Willey, Wixamtree, along with the liberty and the ancient borough of Bedford.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/bedfordshire] There have been several changes to the county boundary; for example, in 1897 Kensworth and part of Caddington were transferred from Hertfordshire to Bedfordshire.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/bedfordshire] The southern end of the county is on the chalk ridge known as the Chiltern Hills.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/bedfordshire] The remainder forms part of the broad drainage basin of the River Great Ouse and its tributaries.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/bedfordshire] Most of Bedfordshire's rocks are clays and sandstones from the Jurassic and Cretaceous periods, with some limestone.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/bedfordshire] Local clay has been used for brick-making of Fletton-style bricks in the Marston Vale.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/bedfordshire] Glacial erosion of chalk has left hard flint nodules deposited as gravel—these have been commercially extracted in the past at pits which are now lakes: at Priory Country Park, Wyboston and Felmersham.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/bedfordshire] The Greensand Ridge is an escarpment across the county from near Leighton Buzzard to near Gamlingay in Cambridgeshire.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/bedfordshire] Bedfordshire, being situated in the east of England, has a relatively dry climate for the UK with regular but generally moderate rainfall.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/bedfordshire] Average annual rainfall is 608.6 millimetres (23.96 in) at Bedford.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/bedfordshire] October is the wettest month, with 65.3 millimetres (2.57 in), and March the driest, with 37.3 millimetres (1.47 in).
[src:corythucha-ciliata/bedfordshire] Although temperatures are usually moderate, the county has one of the largest absolute temperature ranges in the UK – of more than 60 °C (108 °F).
[src:corythucha-ciliata/bedfordshire] Average temperatures in Bedford range from a low of 1.5 °C (34.7 °F) overnight in February to a high of 22.4 °C (72.3 °F) during the day in July.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/bedfordshire] The highest official temperature recorded in Bedfordshire was 39.7 °C (103.5 °F) in 2022.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/bedfordshire] The lowest official temperature recorded in Bedfordshire was −20.6 °C (−5.1 °F) in 1947.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/bedfordshire] The Bedfordshire Police and Crime Commissioner is John Tizard, a member of the Labour Party.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/bedfordshire] For local government purposes, Bedfordshire is divided into three unitary authorities: the boroughs of Bedford and Luton, and the district of Central Bedfordshire.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/bedfordshire] Healthcare in the county is dealt with by a single Clinical Commission Group (CCG), which serves all three local authorities in the county, alongside the City of Milton Keynes in Buckinghamshire.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/bedfordshire] Policing and fire and rescue services continue to be provided on a county-wide basis, with Bedfordshire Police governed by the Bedfordshire Police and Crime Commissioner and Bedfordshire Fire and Rescue Service governed by a Fire Authority comprising members of the three councils.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/bedfordshire] Ambulance Services are provided by the East of England Ambulance Service NHS Trust.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/bedfordshire] The present constituencies date from 1997.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/bedfordshire] The boundaries were slightly modified for the 2010 general election.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/bedfordshire] This is a chart of trend of regional gross value added of Bedfordshire at current basic prices published (pp.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/bedfordshire] 240–253) by *Office for National Statistics* with figures in millions of British Pounds Sterling.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/bedfordshire] Bedfordshire is the location of a number of notable UK and international companies who have either headquarters or major bases in the county.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/bedfordshire] Autoglass, Boxclever and Charles Wells Pubs are all based in Bedford, while the Kier Group and Kingspan Timber Solutions are based in Sandy, and Jordans Cereals are based in Biggleswade.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/bedfordshire] EasyJet, Impellam, TUI Airways and Vauxhall Motors are all based in Luton, Whitbread is based in Houghton Regis and Costa Coffee is now based in Dunstable.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/bedfordshire] UltraVision is based in Leighton Buzzard, while Moto Hospitality is based at Toddington service station.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/bedfordshire] The "Bedfordshire clanger" is a local dish consisting of a suet crust pastry filled with meat in one end and a fruit preserve in the other.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/bedfordshire] It was traditionally a farm labourers' meal, designed so as to produce no waste as well as two separate meals.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/bedfordshire] Chocolate Toothpaste is another local delicacy.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/bedfordshire] A chocolate tart, Chocolate Toothpaste consists of a gritty chocolate filling (said to resemble the texture of toothpaste) within a pastry tart, commonly finished with a swirl of whipped cream on top.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/bedfordshire] The flag of Bedfordshire is based on the banner of arms of the former Bedfordshire County Council.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/bedfordshire] Bedfordshire lies on many of the main transport routes which link London to the Midlands, Northern England and the rest of the UK.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/bedfordshire] Two of England's six main trunk roads pass through Bedfordshire.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/bedfordshire] The A1 London to Edinburgh road (the Great North Road) runs close by Biggleswade and Sandy, and Watling Street, the Roman road between London and Chester, passes through Dunstable.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/bedfordshire] Until it was diverted in 2017, this was also the route of the A5 road between London and Holyhead.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/bedfordshire] The Bedfordshire section of the A5 now runs from junction 11a of the M1 to rejoin Watling Street between Dunstable and Hockliffe, then continues on to cross the Buckinghamshire border at the City of Milton Keynes.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/bedfordshire] To these was added in 1959 the M1 motorway, running from London to Leeds.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/bedfordshire] Running from junctions 10 to 13 in Bedfordshire, there are two junctions serving Luton (at the southern end), with another one serving Bedford and Milton Keynes (at the northern end).
[src:corythucha-ciliata/bedfordshire] Between these lie two other junctions in the county; one connecting to the A5 and serving Dunstable, and the other serving the town of Flitwick.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/bedfordshire] There is one motorway service station in the county: Toddington Services.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/bedfordshire] Former trunk roads, now local roads managed by the local highway authorities, include the A428 (Cambridge-Coventry) running east–west through Bedford Borough, and the A6 from Luton to Carlisle.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/bedfordshire] Three of England's main lines pass through Bedfordshire.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/bedfordshire] The West Coast Main Line has but a short section where it passes through the far west of the county, with one station at Leighton Buzzard served by West Midlands Trains to London Euston and Northampton.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/bedfordshire] The East Coast Main Line has stations at Arlesey, Biggleswade and Sandy, served by Great Northern services to King's Cross and Peterborough.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/bedfordshire] The Midland Main Line serves Luton, Luton Airport (via Luton DART link from the station at Luton Airport Parkway) and Bedford, with trains to many destinations operated by East Midlands Railway and Thameslink.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/bedfordshire] Intermediate stations at Flitwick, Harlington and Leagrave are served by Thameslink.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/bedfordshire] There are London North Western rural services also running between Bedford and Bletchley along the Marston Vale Line.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/bedfordshire] The River Great Ouse links Bedfordshire to the Fenland waterways.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/bedfordshire] As of 2004 there are plans by the Bedford & Milton Keynes Waterway Trust to construct a canal linking the Great Ouse at Bedford to the Grand Union Canal at Milton Keynes, 14 miles (23 km) distant.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/bedfordshire] Luton Airport (the fifth busiest in the United Kingdom) has flights to many UK, European, Middle Eastern and North African destinations, operated largely (but not exclusively) by low-cost airlines.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/bedfordshire] Local news is provided by BBC East and ITV Anglia from Cambridge, the southern part of the county such as Luton can also receive BBC London & ITV London meaning the area can get news and television programmes from Cambridge and London.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/bedfordshire] Local radio stations are BBC Three Counties Radio (broadcast from Dunstable), Heart East, Greatest Hits Radio Bucks, Beds and Herts (formerly Mix 96), BigglesFM (covering Biggleswade, Potton and Sandy), In2beats (Bedford) and Radio LaB (Luton).
[src:corythucha-ciliata/bedfordshire] The five largest settlements in Bedfordshire as of the 2021 UK census.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/bedfordshire] type settlements, currently undergoing significant planned expansion in the county.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/bedfordshire] The state education system for all of Bedfordshire used to be organised by Bedfordshire County Council.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/bedfordshire] Unlike most of the United Kingdom, Bedfordshire County Council operated a three-tier education system arranged into lower, middle and upper schools, as recommended in the Plowden Report of 1967, although Luton continued to operate a two-tier system.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/bedfordshire] The three-tier arrangement continued in the rest of the county, though in 2006 a vote was held with a view to moving to the two-tier model, but this was rejected.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/bedfordshire] After the 2009 structural changes to local government in England, Bedfordshire County Council was abolished, and its responsibilities for education were passed to Bedford Borough Council and Central Bedfordshire Council.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/bedfordshire] Bedford Borough Council voted in November 2009 to change to the two-tier model in its area.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/bedfordshire] The change was due to be introduced over a five-year period and be completed in 2015.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/bedfordshire] However, with the cancellation of the Building Schools for the Future programme in 2010, the borough changed its proposals, and the switch proceeded on school by school basis where council funds allowed.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/bedfordshire] However as of 2020 all of Bedford Borough has a two-tier education structure apart from in the Marston Vale area (one upper school remains).
[src:corythucha-ciliata/bedfordshire] Most of the secondary schools in the area offer sixth form courses (such as A Levels), though Bedford College and The Bedford Sixth Form also offer a range of further education courses.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/bedfordshire] Additionally, Stella Mann College is a private college which offers a range of further education courses relating to the performing arts.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/bedfordshire] There are a number of independent schools, many of which have links to the Harpur Trust.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/bedfordshire] These include Bedford School, Bedford Modern School and Bedford Girls' School.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/bedfordshire] In Central Bedfordshire, the school systems in Dunstable and Sandy have been re-organised into the two-tier model in response to parent and school demand, but elsewhere in the authority the three-tier model continues.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/bedfordshire] Plans for the construction of new settlements in Marston Vale have included lower, middle and upper schools.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/bedfordshire] Luton also operates a three-tier education system, though its organisation of infant, junior and high schools mirrors the traditional transfer age into secondary education of 11 years.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/bedfordshire] However, most of Luton's high schools do not offer sixth-form education.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/bedfordshire] Instead, this is handled by Luton Sixth Form College, though Barnfield College and Cardinal Newman Catholic School, Stockwood Park Academy and The Chalk Hills Academy also offer a range of further education courses.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/bedfordshire] There are two universities based in the county – the University of Bedfordshire and Cranfield University.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/bedfordshire] These institutions attract students from all over the UK and abroad, as well as from Bedfordshire.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/bedfordshire] The enormous Cardington airship sheds are situated to the south of Bedford, near the villages of Cardington and Shortstown.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/bedfordshire] They were originally built for the construction of large airships during World War I.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/bedfordshire] St Paul's Church, Bedford is a Church of England parish church and the Civic Church of the Borough of Bedford and the County of Bedfordshire.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/bedfordshire] Located on St Paul's Square, it is a large medieval and later church of cathedral proportions and spire.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/bedfordshire] St Paul's was the church of the BBC during the Second World War.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/bedfordshire] The Millbrook Proving Ground, near Junction 13 of the M1, has 70 kilometres (43 miles) of varied vehicle test tracks.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/bedfordshire] Bedfordshire is home to League One team Luton Town F.C. and the Ampthill RUFC and Bedford Blues rugby teams, amongst other various sporting teams.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/bedfordshire] Bedfordshire boasts a 40-mile (64 km) walk traversing the county from Leighton Buzzard at the southern endpoint and Sandy, Bedfordshire/Gamlingay in southern Cambridgeshire to the east; this is called the Greensand Ridge Walk.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/bedfordshire] For cyclists, there is a parallel route called the Greensand Cycle Way that follows minor country roads.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/binomial-nomenclature] Such a name is called a **binomial name** (often shortened to just "binomial"), a **binomen**, **binominal name**, or a **scientific name**; more informally, it is also called a **Latin name**.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/binomial-nomenclature] In the International Code of Zoological Nomenclature (ICZN), the system is also called **binominal nomenclature**, with an "n" before the "al" in "binominal", which is *not* a typographic error, meaning "two-name naming system".
[src:corythucha-ciliata/binomial-nomenclature] The first part of the name – the *generic name* – identifies the genus to which the species belongs, whereas the second part – the *specific name* or *specific epithet* – distinguishes the species within the genus.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/binomial-nomenclature] For example, modern humans belong to the genus *Homo* and within this genus to the species *Homo sapiens*.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/binomial-nomenclature] The formal introduction of this system of naming species is credited to Carl Linnaeus, effectively beginning with his work *Species Plantarum* in 1753.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/binomial-nomenclature] But as early as 1622, Gaspard Bauhin introduced in his book *Pinax theatri botanici* (English, *Illustrated Exposition of Plants*) containing many names of genera that were later adopted by Linnaeus.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/binomial-nomenclature] Binomial nomenclature was introduced in order to provide succinct, relatively stable and verifiable names that could be used and understood internationally, unlike common names which are usually different in every language.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/binomial-nomenclature] Although the general principles underlying binomial nomenclature are common to these two codes, there are some differences in the terminology they use and their particular rules.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/binomial-nomenclature] In modern usage, the first letter of the generic name is always capitalized in writing, while that of the specific epithet is not, even when derived from a proper noun such as the name of a person or place.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/binomial-nomenclature] Similarly, both parts are italicized in normal text (or underlined in handwriting).
[src:corythucha-ciliata/binomial-nomenclature] Thus the binomial name of the annual phlox (named after botanist Thomas Drummond) is now written as *Phlox drummondii*.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/binomial-nomenclature] Often, after a species name is introduced in a text, the generic name is abbreviated to the first letter in subsequent mentions (e.g., *P. drummondii*).
[src:corythucha-ciliata/binomial-nomenclature] In scientific works, the authority for a binomial name is usually given, at least when it is first mentioned, and the year of publication may also be specified.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/binomial-nomenclature] The word *binomial* is composed of two elements: *bi-* (Latin prefix meaning 'two') and *nomial* (the adjective form of *nomen*, Latin for 'name').
[src:corythucha-ciliata/binomial-nomenclature] In Medieval Latin, the related word *binomium* was used to signify one term in a binomial expression in mathematics.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/binomial-nomenclature] In fact, the Latin word *binomium* may validly refer to either of the epithets in the binomial name, which can equally be referred to as a *binomen* (pl.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/binomial-nomenclature] Before the adoption of the modern binomial system of naming species, a scientific name consisted of a generic name combined with a specific name that was from one to several words long.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/binomial-nomenclature] Together they formed a system of polynomial nomenclature.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/binomial-nomenclature] These names had two separate functions: to designate or label the species, and to be a diagnosis or description.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/binomial-nomenclature] These two goals were eventually found to be incompatible.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/binomial-nomenclature] Such "polynomial names" may sometimes look like binomials, but are different.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/binomial-nomenclature] For example, Gerard's herbal (as amended by Johnson) describes various kinds of spiderwort: "The first is called *Phalangium ramosum*, Branched Spiderwort; the second, *Phalangium non ramosum*, Unbranched Spiderwort.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/binomial-nomenclature] The other ... is aptly termed *Phalangium Ephemerum Virginianum*, Soon-Fading Spiderwort of Virginia".
[src:corythucha-ciliata/binomial-nomenclature] The Latin phrases are short descriptions, rather than identifying labels.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/binomial-nomenclature] The Bauhins, in particular Caspar Bauhin (1560–1624), took some important steps towards the binomial system by pruning the Latin descriptions, in many cases to two words.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/binomial-nomenclature] The adoption by biologists of a system of strictly binomial nomenclature is due to Swedish botanist and physician Carl Linnaeus (1707–1778).
[src:corythucha-ciliata/binomial-nomenclature] It was in his 1753 *Species Plantarum* that Linnaeus began consistently using a one-word **trivial name** (*nomen triviale*) after a generic name (genus name) in a system of binomial nomenclature.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/binomial-nomenclature] Trivial names had already appeared in his *Critica Botanica* (1737) and *Philosophia Botanica* (1751).
[src:corythucha-ciliata/binomial-nomenclature] This trivial name is what is now known as a specific epithet (*ICNafp*) or specific name (*ICZN*).
[src:corythucha-ciliata/binomial-nomenclature] The Bauhins' genus names were retained in many of these, but the descriptive part was reduced to a single word.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/binomial-nomenclature] Linnaeus's trivial names introduced the idea that the function of a name could simply be to give a species a unique label, meaning that the name no longer needed to be descriptive.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/binomial-nomenclature] Both parts could, for example, be derived from the names of people.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/binomial-nomenclature] Thus Gerard's *Phalangium ephemerum virginianum* became *Tradescantia virginiana*, where the genus name honoured John Tradescant the Younger, an English botanist and gardener.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/binomial-nomenclature] A bird in the parrot family was named *Psittacus alexandri*, meaning "Alexander's parrot", after Alexander the Great, whose armies introduced eastern parakeets to Greece.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/binomial-nomenclature] Linnaeus's trivial names were much easier to remember and use than the parallel polynomial names, and eventually replaced them.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/binomial-nomenclature] Nowadays, many species are mainly referred to by their binomial names, even in non-specialized fields, such as environmental education and the internet in general.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/binomial-nomenclature] Because of this use, the binomial *Tyrannosaurus rex* is widely known.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/binomial-nomenclature] Binomial nomenclature for species has the effect that when a species is moved from one genus to another, sometimes the specific name or epithet must be changed as well.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/binomial-nomenclature] This may happen because the specific name is already used in the new genus, or to agree in gender with the new genus if the specific epithet is an adjective modifying the genus name.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/binomial-nomenclature] Some biologists have argued for the combination of the genus name and specific epithet into a single unambiguous name, or for the use of uninomials (as used in nomenclature of ranks above species).
[src:corythucha-ciliata/binomial-nomenclature] Because genus names are unique only within a nomenclature code, it is possible for homonyms (two or more species sharing the same genus name) to happen, and even the same binomial if they occur in different kingdoms.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/binomial-nomenclature] At least 1,258 instances of genus name duplication occur (mainly between zoology and botany).
[src:corythucha-ciliata/binomial-nomenclature] Nomenclature (including binomial nomenclature) is not the same as classification, although the two are related.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/binomial-nomenclature] Classification is the ordering of items into groups based on similarities or differences; in biological classification, species are one of the kinds of item to be classified.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/binomial-nomenclature] In principle, the names given to species could be completely independent of their classification.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/binomial-nomenclature] This is not the case for binomial names, since the first part of a binomial is the name of the genus into which the species is placed.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/binomial-nomenclature] The independence is only partial since the names of families and other higher taxa are usually based on genera.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/binomial-nomenclature] Taxonomy includes both nomenclature and classification.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/binomial-nomenclature] Its first stages (sometimes called "alpha taxonomy") are concerned with finding, describing and naming species of living or fossil organisms.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/binomial-nomenclature] Binomial nomenclature is thus an important part of taxonomy as it is the system by which species are named.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/binomial-nomenclature] Taxonomists are also concerned with classification, including its principles, procedures and rules.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/binomial-nomenclature] A complete binomial name is always treated grammatically as if it were a phrase in the Latin language (hence the common use of the term "Latin name" for a binomial name).
[src:corythucha-ciliata/binomial-nomenclature] However, the two parts of a binomial name can each be derived from a number of sources, of which Latin is only one.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/binomial-nomenclature] The first part of the name, which identifies the genus, must be a word that can be treated as a Latin singular noun in the nominative case.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/binomial-nomenclature] It must be unique within the purview of each nomenclatural code, but can be repeated between them.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/binomial-nomenclature] Thus *Huia recurvata* is an extinct species of plant, found as fossils in Yunnan, China, whereas *Huia masonii* is a species of frog found in Java, Indonesia.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/binomial-nomenclature] The second part of the name, which identifies the species within the genus, is also treated grammatically as a Latin word.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/binomial-nomenclature] Whereas the first part of a binomial name must be unique within the purview of each nomenclatural code, the second part is quite commonly used in two or more genera (as is shown by examples of *hodgsonii* above), but cannot be used more than once within a single genus.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/binomial-nomenclature] The full binomial name must be unique within each code.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/binomial-nomenclature] From the early 19th century onwards, it became ever more apparent that a body of rules was necessary to govern scientific names.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/binomial-nomenclature] In the course of time these became nomenclature codes.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/binomial-nomenclature] Virus names are governed by the *International Committee on Taxonomy of Viruses* (*ICTV*), a taxonomic code, which determines taxa as well as names.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/binomial-nomenclature] Unifying the different codes into a single code, the "*BioCode*", has been suggested, although implementation is not in sight.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/binomial-nomenclature] (There is also a published code for a different system of biotic nomenclature, which does not use ranks above species, but instead names clades.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/binomial-nomenclature] As noted above, there are some differences between the codes in how binomials can be formed; for example the *ICZN* allows both parts to be the same, while the *ICNafp* does not.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/binomial-nomenclature] Another difference is in how personal names are used in forming specific names or epithets.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/binomial-nomenclature] The *ICNafp* sets out precise rules by which a personal name is to be converted to a specific epithet.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/binomial-nomenclature] In particular, names ending in a consonant (but not "er") are treated as first being converted into Latin by adding "-ius" (for a man) or "-ia" (for a woman), and then being made genitive (i.e. meaning "of that person or persons").
[src:corythucha-ciliata/binomial-nomenclature] This produces specific epithets like *lecardii* for Lecard (male), *wilsoniae* for Wilson (female), and *brauniarum* for the Braun sisters.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/binomial-nomenclature] By contrast, the *ICZN* does not require the intermediate creation of a Latin form of a personal name, allowing the genitive ending to be added directly to the personal name.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/binomial-nomenclature] This explains the difference between the names of the plant *Magnolia hodgsonii* and the bird *Anthus hodgsoni*.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/binomial-nomenclature] Furthermore, the *ICNafp* requires names not published in the form required by the code to be corrected to conform to it, whereas the *ICZN* is more protective of the form used by the original author.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/binomial-nomenclature] By tradition, the binomial names of species are usually typeset in italics; for example, *Homo sapiens*.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/binomial-nomenclature] Generally, the binomial should be printed in a font style different from that used in the normal text; for example, "*Several more*Homo sapiens*fossils were discovered*." When handwritten, a binomial name should be underlined; for example, Homo sapiens.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/binomial-nomenclature] The first part of the binomial, the genus name, is always written with an initial capital letter.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/binomial-nomenclature] Older sources, particularly botanical works published before the 1950s, used a different convention: if the second part of the name was derived from a proper noun, e.g., the name of a person or place, a capital letter was used.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/binomial-nomenclature] Thus, the modern form *Berberis darwinii* was written as *Berberis Darwinii*.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/binomial-nomenclature] A capital was also used when the name is formed by two nouns in apposition, e.g., *Panthera Leo* or *Centaurea Cyanus*.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/binomial-nomenclature] In current usage, the second part is never written with an initial capital.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/binomial-nomenclature] When used with a common name, the scientific name often follows in parentheses, although this varies with publication.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/binomial-nomenclature] The binomial name should generally be written in full.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/binomial-nomenclature] For example, a list of members of the genus *Canis* might be written as "*Canis lupus*, *C. aureus*, *C. simensis*".
[src:corythucha-ciliata/binomial-nomenclature] The abbreviation "sp." is used when the actual specific name cannot or need not be specified.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/binomial-nomenclature] The abbreviation "spp." (standing for *species pluralis*, Latin for "multiple species") indicates "several species".
[src:corythucha-ciliata/binomial-nomenclature] These abbreviations are not italicised (or underlined).
[src:corythucha-ciliata/binomial-nomenclature] For example: "*Canis* sp." means "an unspecified species of the genus *Canis*", while "*Canis* spp." means "two or more species of the genus *Canis*".
[src:corythucha-ciliata/binomial-nomenclature] (These abbreviations should not be confused with the abbreviations "ssp." (zoology) or "subsp." (botany), plurals "sspp." or "subspp.", referring to one or more subspecies.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/binomial-nomenclature] The abbreviation "cf." (i.e., *confer* in Latin) is used to compare individuals/taxa with known/described species.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/binomial-nomenclature] Conventions for use of the "cf." qualifier vary.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/binomial-nomenclature] In paleontology, it is typically used when the identification is not confirmed.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/binomial-nomenclature] *nasicus*" was used to indicate "a fossil bird similar to the Cuban crow but not certainly identified as this species".
[src:corythucha-ciliata/binomial-nomenclature] In molecular systematics papers, "cf." may be used to indicate one or more undescribed species assumed to be related to a described species.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/binomial-nomenclature] *spectabile*" because they had been viewed as related to, but distinct from, *Etheostoma spectabile* (orangethroat darter).
[src:corythucha-ciliata/binomial-nomenclature] This view was supported to varying degrees by DNA analysis.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/binomial-nomenclature] The somewhat informal use of taxa names with qualifying abbreviations is referred to as open nomenclature and it is not subject to strict usage codes.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/binomial-nomenclature] In some contexts, the dagger symbol ("†") may be used before or after the binomial name to indicate that the species is extinct.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/binomial-nomenclature] In scholarly texts, at least the first or main use of the binomial name is usually followed by the "authority" – a way of designating the scientist(s) who first published the name.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/binomial-nomenclature] The authority is written in slightly different ways in zoology and botany.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/binomial-nomenclature] For names governed by the *ICZN* the surname is usually written in full together with the date (normally only the year) of publication.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/binomial-nomenclature] The International Plant Names Index maintains an approved list of botanical author abbreviations.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/binomial-nomenclature] Historically, abbreviations were used in zoology too.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/binomial-nomenclature] When the original name is changed, e.g., the species is moved to a different genus, both codes use parentheses around the original authority; the *ICNafp* also requires the person who made the change to be given.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/binomial-nomenclature] In the *ICNafp*, the original name is then called the basionym.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/binomial-nomenclature] Binomial nomenclature, as described here, is a system for naming species.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/binomial-nomenclature] Implicitly, it includes a system for naming genera, since the first part of the name of the species is a genus name.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/binomial-nomenclature] In a classification system based on ranks, there are also ways of naming ranks above the level of genus and below the level of species.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/binomial-nomenclature] Ranks above genus (e.g., family, order, class) receive one-part names, which are conventionally not written in italics.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/binomial-nomenclature] Thus, the house sparrow, *Passer domesticus*, belongs to the family Passeridae.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/binomial-nomenclature] Family names are normally based on genus names, such as in zoology, although the endings used differ between zoology and botany.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/binomial-nomenclature] Ranks below species receive three-part names, conventionally written in italics like the names of species.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/binomial-nomenclature] There are significant differences between the *ICZN* and the *ICNafp*.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/binomial-nomenclature] In zoology, the only formal rank below species is subspecies and the name is written simply as three parts (a trinomen).
[src:corythucha-ciliata/binomial-nomenclature] Thus, one of the subspecies of the olive-backed pipit is *Anthus hodgsoni berezowskii*.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/binomial-nomenclature] Informally, in some circumstances, a form may be appended, though such names are unavailable, and have no formal standing in zoological nomenclature (i.e., they have no recognized author or date, and do not compete for homonymy).
[src:corythucha-ciliata/binomial-nomenclature] *spectabilis* is the harlequin ladybird in its black or melanic forms having four large orange or red spots.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/binomial-nomenclature] In botany, there are many ranks below species and although the name itself is written in three parts, a "connecting term" (not part of the name) is needed to show the rank.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/binomial-nomenclature] Thus, the American black elder is *Sambucus nigra* subsp.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/binomial-nomenclature] *canadensis*; the white-flowered form of the ivy-leaved cyclamen is *Cyclamen hederifolium* f.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/corythucha-ciliata] It originates in the New World, but has been introduced and has spread in Europe.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/corythucha-ciliata] It is a small, whitish insect and feeds on the underside of the leaves, sucking sap.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/corythucha-ciliata] There are reports in Europe of *C. cilata* landing on people and biting them.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/corythucha-ciliata] Reports from Italy, France and Romania indicate that some people experience adverse reactions, e.g., dermatosis.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/corythucha-ciliata] The adult sycamore lace bug is milky white in colour and between 3.2 and 3.7 mm (0.13 and 0.15 in) in length.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/corythucha-ciliata] It is similar in appearance to the cotton lace bug (*Corythucha gossypii*) and the Florida oak lace bug (*Corythucha floridana*), but lacks the brown crescent-shaped band on the carina (ridge on the body-wall) of the former and is larger than the latter.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/corythucha-ciliata] The only brown colour is a small spot on the protuberance on each elytron (wing-case).
[src:corythucha-ciliata/corythucha-ciliata] The nymphs are oval in shape, dorso-ventrally flattened, black and prickly.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/corythucha-ciliata] This lace bug can most easily be distinguished from other species by its presence on sycamore.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/corythucha-ciliata] In Europe the sycamore lacebug was first observed in 1964 in Padova, Italy, and has since spread throughout Southern and Central Europe with populations are far east as Uzbekistan, infesting the London plane (*Platanus × hispanica*).
[src:corythucha-ciliata/corythucha-ciliata] Although it does not by itself kill trees, in Central Europe it is often found in association with two plant-pathogenic fungi which can kill trees, *Apiognomonia veneta* and *Ceratocystis fimbriata*, leading to the hypothesis that it may act as a vector for these fungi.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/corythucha-ciliata] Feeding causes leaves to show chlorotic stippling (light coloured marks from lack of chlorophyll) near leaf veins which can spread across the entire leaf causing them to lighten or bronze, ultimately leading to premature falling.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/corythucha-ciliata] The effects of this are most notable in late summer.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/corythucha-ciliata] Whilst widespread in mainland Europe, it's not considered endemic to the United Kingdom.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/corythucha-ciliata] In 2006, outbreaks were discovered by agents from the Plant Health and Seeds Inspectorate (PHSI) at two nurseries in Bedfordshire along with a stand of plane trees nearby.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/corythucha-ciliata] The insects were found to have infected both London and Oriental plane trees imported from France and Italy, as well as mature plane trees on the site.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/corythucha-ciliata] It was assumed the species was established however no further sightings were reported until 2023.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/corythucha-ciliata] After the adults have mated, the female lays eggs on the undersides of leaves of the host tree, usually near a fork in the veins.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/corythucha-ciliata] When the eggs hatch, the juveniles stay close together at first, only moving onto a new leaf at the fourth instar stage.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/corythucha-ciliata] They puncture the epidermis of the leaf with their mouth parts and suck sap.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/corythucha-ciliata] There are five instars, after which the nymphs undergo incomplete metamorphosis to become adults.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/corythucha-ciliata] During the summer in Oklahoma, the whole cycle takes about 44 days.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/corythucha-ciliata] In the warmer parts of the insect's range, between 19 °C (66 °F) and 33 °C (91 °F) being considered ideal, there may be several generations (1–3) each year.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/corythucha-ciliata] The insects are restricted to the underside of the leaves where little black mounds of dried frass can be seen and the shed skins of the nymphs often adhere to the leaf.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/corythucha-ciliata] The upper surface of the leaf is speckled with white, near the veins at first, and the leaf becomes progressively paler or bronzed and may fall early.
[src:corythucha-ciliata/corythucha-ciliata] Overwintering generally takes place as adults in crevices or under flakes of bark, the insects being able to withstand temperatures down to at least −24 °C (−11 °F).
